article.headline: Arenas: 21 points, 13 assists, 12 rebounds
article.linkText: With Arenas' triple-double, Wizards tame Bulls
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- "Gilbert!" yelled Kwame Brown across the Washington Wizards' locker room. "Curse me out before you leave. Please." Laughter erupted, the feud between the two players suddenly not so tense after the Wizards converted it into a two-game winning streak. One night after staging a mini-mutiny on offense, Gilbert Arenas set aside his tiff with Brown and earned his second career triple-double to lead the Wizards to Thursday night's 95-87 victory over the Chicago Bulls. "Whatever y'all are doing, keep it going, because he's playing like an All-Star now," Brown told reporters. "Y'all made it drama. We said what we said, and it was the truth. And now guys are playing together. We've won two in a row." Arenas scored 21 points, grabbed 12 rebounds and handed out 13 assists as the Wizards completed rare back-to-back victories. Arenas' first triple-double came earlier this season, a 25-12-10 effort against Dallas on Nov. 5. On Wednesday, Arenas didn't attempt a shot until 5:30 remained in a two-point victory at Toronto -- and that was only after coach Eddie Jordan threatened to bench him. Arenas had been smarting from comments made Sunday by Brown, who accused an unnamed teammate of being too selfish with the ball. Arenas responded by criticizing Brown's play. "I guess that's what we need, a little kick in the butt, huh?" said Arenas, whose matched a career-high in rebounds and had a season-high in assists. Added Brown: "That's how you play basketball. Everybody had a touch. We weren't standing there watching. ... Whatever happened, I would do it all over again -- if we can keep playing like this." Brown had 15 points and 13 rebounds, and every Wizards starter took at least nine shots. Somehow trying to manage this was coach Jordan, who absolutely did not want to attribute the team's better play to the Arenas-Brown saga. "I'm trying to do a good explaining something that I don't know what's going on," Jordan said. "Everything we've been talking about for months -- and I don't know why it's turned around. Is it because of that? Maybe it is, but I'd rather not make a statement that something negative made this happen." Of course, it helps that the Wizards played two struggling teams. The Bulls, led by Kirk Hinrich's 23 points, lost their fourth straight. Chicago's entire scoring output in the first 10 minutes of the fourth quarter consisted of a 3-pointer (Hinrich), a 2-pointer (Eddie Robinson) and a 1-pointer (free throw by Eddy Curry). The Bulls got Kendall Gill off the injured list but lost Jerome Williams to a strained left knee tendon in the first quarter. Tyson Chandler didn't play at all, the first time he's sat for an entire game this season while healthy, a move coach Scott Skiles simply called a "coach's decision." "I don't know how you could put a freeze on me," Chandler said. "I'm playing the minutes that he's giving me, and the minutes that he's giving me I play hard. I just wasn't in his rotation tonight." Arenas passed up a fast-break opportunity on the Wizards' first possession, but then got the ball back and took his first shot -- a 3-pointer from the left baseline that missed. He didn't score until making a jump shot in the second quarter, but he wowed the crowd with a one-handed flying dunk late in the half. Arenas hit a pair of 3-pointers that helped the Wizards make up an 11-point deficit in the third quarter. An acrobatic layup gave his team its first lead of the second half, 67-65 late in the quarter, and Washington never trailed again. The Wizards will be hard-pressed to run their winning streak to three, as Jordan was reminded when someone mentioned the next opponent coming to town Saturday. "Bring on the Lakers," Jordan said with a laugh.

Game notes
Halftime adjustment from the refs: The fouls went 13-4 against the Wizards in the first half, then 19-4 against the Bulls in the second half. ... Williams' injury will be evaluated Friday. ... The Bulls activated Gill and placed Chris Jeffries on the injured list with lower back pain. Gill had been on the injured list since Jan. 25 with a strained right Achilles' tendon. Gill played 26 minutes and scored 15 points. ... Washington's 10 first-quarter assists were a season-high for a quarter.
